Third-party attributions
========================

The following projects influenced Mantis's design or were studied
during its development. All Mantis code is original and written from
scratch in Rust; these projects are credited as inspiration, not as
imported code.

Hacker Bob
----------
  Upstream:    https://github.com/vmihalis/hacker-bob
  License:     Apache License, Version 2.0
  Copyright:   2026 Michail Vasileiadis and contributors

  The MCP-tool-orchestrated workflow that Mantis adopted in
  `crates/mantis-mcp` (replacing the rigid `mantis pentest` poll
  loop with an LLM-driven engagement loop) was directly inspired by
  Hacker Bob's local-MCP runtime model — particularly its decision
  to expose engagement primitives as MCP tools and let the host LLM
  own the state machine.

  The wave/handoff pattern for parallel hunter agents in
  `crates/mantis-mcp/src/wave.rs` and the corresponding
  `mantis-hunter` sub-agent, `/mantis:wave` slash command, and
  FAN_OUT phase in `mantis-orchestrator.md` are also inspired by
  Hacker Bob's `bounty_start_next_wave` / `bounty_write_wave_handoff`
  / `bounty_merge_wave_handoffs` mechanism for fan-out hunter waves
  with merged handoff reconciliation.

  Specific Hacker Bob files studied for the hack-phase deeper
  inspiration (no source ported, only architectural ideas):
    - `prompts/roles/hunter.md` — the "never record as standalone"
      hunter-discipline list (missing headers, banner disclosure,
      SPF/DKIM/DMARC, GraphQL introspection, CORS wildcard, open
      redirect, etc.). This drives the `mantis-hunter.md`
      "Hunter discipline" section and the chain-attempt requirement
      for those defect classes.
    - `prompts/roles/chain.md` — the chain-attempt model with terminal
      outcomes (confirmed/denied/blocked/inconclusive/not_applicable)
      and the severity ladder (LOW+LOW=LOW; max input+1 without
      rationale; max input+2 with `elevation:` rationale; no
      jump-the-rung). Both the outcome enum and the ladder are
      ported verbatim into `crates/mantis-mcp/src/wave.rs`.
    - `prompts/roles/evidence.md` — the evidence-pack model
      (representative_samples, replay_summary, report_snippet).
      Not yet ported in this slice but informs the planned
      `mantis_record_evidence_pack` tool.
    - `prompts/playbooks/C2_doc_vs_behavior.md` and
      `C4_multi_account_differential.md` — the capability-playbook
      shape (one-paragraph differential workflow). The Mantis
      playbooks under `plugin/claude-code/playbooks/cap-*.md` follow
      the same convention but are written from scratch.
    - `mcp/lib/capability-playbooks.js` — the directory layout
      convention (playbooks live as flat markdown files keyed by
      capability id). Mantis mirrors this in
      `plugin/claude-code/playbooks/`.
    - `mcp/lib/chain-attempts.js` — the JSONL + atomic-append model
      for chain attempts. Mantis re-implements this in Rust with
      `record_chain_attempt` writing to
      `waves/<n>/chain-attempts.jsonl`.

  All Rust code in `crates/` and Mantis-original playbook markdown is
  written from scratch. Mantis's MCP server is an independent Rust
  implementation built on the `rmcp` crate; no Node.js source from
  Hacker Bob was copied.

  However, Mantis's Claude Code / Codex plugin surface
  (`plugin/claude-code/agents/`, `plugin/claude-code/commands/`,
  `prompts/roles/`) contains files ported verbatim from Hacker Bob
  with `bounty_*` MCP tool calls renamed to `mantis_*` and session
  paths retargeted. The workflow logic, severity heuristics,
  capability-pack table, and completion markers (renamed from
  `BOB_*_DONE` to `MANTIS_*_DONE`) are preserved verbatim. See
  `CONTRAST.md` for the per-file inventory and
  https://github.com/vmihalis/hacker-bob/tree/main/.claude/agents
  for the upstream originals.

